      "anchor_proposed": {
        "vr_id": 42561,
        "reference": "Col 3:16",
        "strongs": "G3056",
        "translit": "logos",
        "anchor_rationale": "'Let the word of Christ dwell in you richly.' The logos as inner-dwelling presence is most clearly named here. The word of Christ is not merely heard or read — it takes up residence (oikeitō) within the person richly, shaping wisdom and producing community formation. The command assumes that the word has an inner location in the person, and that its richness of dwelling is something to be desired and cultivated."
      }
    },
    {
      "code": "M15-H-VCG02",
      "label": "Human speech as communicative act evaluated by its inner quality",
      "context_description": "The term names logos as the communicative act of the human person — evaluated by whether it is intelligible (reaching the inner person of the hearer), gracious and seasoned (shaping the encounter), consistent with deeds, or alternatively empty, arrogant, and inconsistent. The word-as-speech is the outward expression of the inner person and is evaluated by what inner reality it carries. Inner-being phenomenon: speech as the outward expression of inner quality.",
